If an opponent puts up a zone defence, it is necessary to understand why they are doing it, why they find the weaknesses of this defence and how they can exploit them.
The basic principles of engagement against zone defences used by teams are as follows.
Try to break up the zone with a quick attack before it is built;
Preferably only run the ball for passing under the ring in search of an attack;
Any receipt of the ball should show a threat, so the ball should be received in a comfortable attacking position;
If attempting to "break up" a zone from the inside, it should first be stretched with perimeter passes, making sure to threaten the ring with a shot, and then attempt to bring the ball to the penalty line or make a pass under the ring with the lead;
When trying to break up a zone with free throws, it is important to move the ball around the perimeter as quickly as possible and for players to move so as to occupy areas of the court where there are no defenders;
Most combinations used against a personal defence can also be used against a zone defence;
Players must be able to recognise when and what kind of zone defence an opponent is using;
One effective "breakdown" of a zone defence is to overload (numerical advantage) the players on one side of the court;
Only take shots at the ring from prepared situations, when some players are ready to go for the rebound and others are ready to cover the rear
